<DOC><DOCNO> AP880830-0145 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-88 2021EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-ForestFires-Glance     08-30 0725</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Forest Fires-Glance,0768</SECOND><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Here is a brief outline of forest fire conditions Tuesday in theWestern states:</TEXT><HEAD>WYOMING:</HEAD><TEXT>   Eight forest fires are burning in Yellowstone National Park withfour in the surrounding national forests in northwestern Wyoming.   The Yellowstone Fires, some of which have spread out into theforests, had charred about 450,000 acres of the 2.2 million-acrepark. The largest fire outside Yellowstone, the Mink Creek fire,covers 107,960 acres of the Bridger-Teton National Forest.   Yellowstone officials said they have spent $54.4 millionfighting fires and about 8,400 firefighters, including hundreds ofArmy soldiers, are working in the area.   Unusually dry weather and a rash of lightning storms opened thefire season early this year, with the first Yellowstone firesreported in June.</TEXT><HEAD>MONTANA:</HEAD><TEXT>   Eight major fires had burned 177,000 acres of Montana forestsTuesday, including two that erupted into serious threats overnight.They ranged in size up to 41,000 acres. Four, totaling 128,700acres, were in designated wilderness areas, including one that hadspread into Yellowstone National Park. Firefighters were gainingthe upper hand on most, however, and no populated areas werethreatened.</TEXT><HEAD>IDAHO:</HEAD><TEXT>   More than 2,500 firefighters, backed up by dozens of NationalGuardsmen, were on the lines against the worst of 17 fires burningover 70,000 acres from the Panhandle National Forest to the CaribouNational Forest on the Wyoming border.   No structures were in imminent danger, but crews were protectingsummer homes from the 16,000-acre Battle Axe wilderness firenortheast of Challis, a communications site from the 330-acre WestJay fire in the Clearwater National Forest east of Lewiston andranches from the 5,000-acre Trail Creek fire near the Wyomingborder in the Caribou. Some $3 million in commercial timber hasbeen lost, mostly to the 7,400-acre Eagle Bar fire near HellsCanyon on the Oregon border.   The terrain is parched by a second straight year of drought, andGov. Cecil Andrus has put the entire state under an extreme fireemergency.</TEXT><HEAD>OREGON:</HEAD><TEXT>   Forces battling Oregon's biggest forest fire, the 31,000-acrelightning-sparked Tepee Butte blaze in the northeastern corner ofthe state, were doubled Tuesday to 545 people, said spokesman RonDeHart.   The Walker Mountain fire outside Grants Pass was containedMonday night at 2,150 acres.   In the eastern high desert, a fire at a cement plant in Durkeequickly burned through 5,000 acres of rangeland, and a trash firetouched off 527 acres on the Warm Springs Indian Reservation.</TEXT><HEAD>CALIFORNIA:</HEAD><TEXT>   Nearly 9,500 lightning strikes Monday and early Tuesday ignitedmore than 100 brush and timber blazes in California, a year after asimilar storm spawned devastating firestorms, officials said.   Although most of the fires were kept small, to the size of anacre or less, firefighters said they were by hot, windy weather inthe drought-parched forests.   The town of Portola in the northern Sierra Nevada, about 180miles northeast of San Francisco, narrowly escaped flames Mondaynight when lightning-caused fires swept together. The fires thathad burned about 1,000 acres were 60 percent contained Tuesday.</TEXT><HEAD>WASHINGTON:</HEAD><TEXT>   The Forest Service said it battled fires on an estimated 22,530acres during the past week, said Ron DeHart of a multi-agency fireregional fire coordinating center at Portland, Ore.   Tim Boyd of the state Department of Natural Resources said thatagency had fought 690 fires on 5,557 acres of private and stateland as of Sunday. That figure does not include the 1,500-acreAeneas Creek blaze northeast of Republic, nor several smaller firesof less than 100 acres in eastern Washington.</TEXT><HEAD>UTAH:</HEAD><TEXT>   Firefighters hoped to declare control over a 525-acre fire nearnorthern Utah's Pineview Reservoir. Crews also were getting theupper hand on two small fires, the 60-acre North Millcreek blaze,in eastern Utah's Uinta Mountains, and the 30-acre ButterfieldCanyon fire in Salt Lake County.   No injuries or damage were reported in any of the fires, andauthorities said no structures were threatened.</TEXT><HEAD>ALASKA:</HEAD><TEXT>   As of Tuesday, there were 30 fires still smoldering on 2 millionacres in rural Alaska, the federal Bureau of Land Management said.   ``We're monitoring them, but not fighting them,'' said SueMitchell, a spokeswoman for the agency. ``I don't think we have anyblazing, active fires right now.''   So far this year, fires have charred 2.1 million acres of landin Alaska.</TEXT></DOC>